    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-10-28T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-10-28T21:00:00-05:00" n="868"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d868">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">300.115(39)/35: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-10-28T21:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 28, 1939—9 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1320. Washington attorneys representing American Cotton Shippers Association, a
                    national trade association of exporters of cotton, file protest regarding “the
                    unreasonably long detention at Gibraltar of ships carrying American cotton to
                    Mediterranean neutral ports.” Protest further reads: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“About twelve ships have been so detained and as the cotton carried is
                            largely on a ‘cash on arrival’ basis, increased costs have been imposed
                            on the members of this Association.</p>
                        <p>As an example, the Lykes Bros, ship, S. S. <hi rend="italic">Oakman</hi>,
                            has been detained for more than 10 days. It carries 10,300 bales of
                            cotton for Barcelona shipped in accordance with arrangements between the
                            Export-Import Bank and the Spanish Government, and 839 bales for Genoa,
                            Italy. Apparently the only other cargo of this vessel was 2,000 tons of
                            petroleum coke booked for Genoa long before the outbreak of the
                            war.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Communicate these facts to the appropriate British authorities and request full
                    statement of the circumstances which they rely upon as justification for the
                    action complained of.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
